"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 7–8
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/matthew.json (adds ch7-8)

Historical/cultural/geographical context focus only.
NOT Greek lexical analysis (mkt-original) and NOT typology/Christology (mkt-christ).

Key context decisions for this range:
- Ch7 judgment sayings: Second Temple wisdom tradition on discernment vs. condemnation
- "Pearls before swine" (7:6): Gentile uncleanness associations; pigs as symbols of Rome
- Golden Rule (7:12): parallel in Hillel ("what is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbor")
- Narrow gate (7:13-14): the Two Ways tradition in Deut 30, Jer 21:8, and Didache 1-6
- False prophets (7:15-23): charismatic claims were common in Second Temple period
- House on rock/sand (7:24-27): Palestinian rainy-season flooding of wadis
- Leper healing (8:1-4): Levitical isolation laws (Lev 13-14) and priestly verification procedure
- Centurion (8:5-13): Roman military presence in Galilee; the centurion as patron-client actor
- "Let the dead bury their dead" (8:22): Jewish burial obligation as highest family duty
- Sea of Galilee (8:23-27): katabatic storms descending from the Golan Heights
- Gadarene demoniacs (8:28-34): Decapolis Gentile territory; pigs as economically significant
- v7:28 and 8:5 already covered in existing JSON; merge_comm will skip those
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: Historical/cultural/geographical context for Matthew 7-8; covers the Sermon
#   conclusion and the Galilean healing narratives. No Greek lexical focus here.
# CHANGE? If verse keys change in data/interlinear/matthew.json, update dict keys here.
# VERIFY: Run script; confirm ch7 = 29 verses, ch8 = 34 verses in output.

MATTHEW = {
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>The command not to judge (<em>mē krinete</em>) operates in the context of Second Temple Jewish communal life, where public shaming and social ostracism were powerful instruments of moral enforcement. In honor-shame culture, public pronouncements of judgment carried enormous social weight; they assigned people to categories of honor or disgrace that affected their economic and social survival. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 prohibition targets the community practice of sitting in judgment over others\xe2\x80\x99 standing before God — a divine prerogative being usurped by human agents.</p><p>The saying does not prohibit all discernment (vv.6,15-20 require discrimination); it targets the posture of condemning others while ignoring one\xe2\x80\x99s own moral condition.</p>',
    "2": '<p>The principle of reciprocal measure (<em>en hō̧ gar krimati krinete</em>) is embedded in Wisdom tradition and Torah: Lev 19:18; Prov 21:13 (whoever shuts his ears to the cry of the poor will cry out himself); the rabbinic <em>middah k\'neged middah</em> (measure for measure) principle. The Mishnah records debates about proportional divine recompense. Jesus appeals to a well-understood framework: the moral universe responds in kind to how one treats others.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The mote-and-beam parable belongs to the wisdom genre of comic hyperbole — a standard rhetorical tool in both Jewish and Greco-Roman instruction. The <em>karphos</em> (splinter, speck) versus <em>dokos</em> (rafter, beam) contrast is deliberately absurd: the visual impossibility of seeing with a rafter lodged in one\xe2\x80\x99s eye while examining a neighbor\xe2\x80\x99s speck satirizes the censorious critic. Rabbinic literature similarly used exaggerated comparisons to expose moral blindness (e.g., <em>b. Arakin</em> 16b on rebuking while guilty).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The question form (<em>pōs ereis</em> = how will you say) is a classic rhetorical challenge in Wisdom literature that forces the listener to recognize the absurdity of their position. The dialogue format mirrors rabbinic disputation style, where a legal principle is first stated, then tested by a hypothetical that exposes its limits or contradictions.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The sequence — first remove the beam, then help with the speck — does not abolish the practice of moral guidance and correction; it prescribes the proper order. The corrected person (<em>hypokritēs</em>) can then see clearly to assist the neighbor. In Second Temple ethics, fraternal correction (<em>hocheah tochiach</em>, Lev 19:17) was a communal obligation — one was to rebuke a neighbor rather than bear sin because of silence. Jesus reframes the obligation: self-examination precedes corrective speech.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The prohibition on giving "what is holy to dogs" and "pearls to swine" employs two animals associated with Gentile uncleanness in Jewish thought. Dogs were street scavengers, not pets; pigs were ritually unclean (Lev 11:7-8; Deut 14:8) and economically central to Roman culture — in Second Temple Jewish consciousness, swine were associated with the Seleucid desecration (1 Macc 1:47; 2 Macc 6:18) and with Roman military insignia (the Tenth Legion stationed near Jerusalem had a boar emblem). The saying likely addresses wisdom about when and to whom the mysteries of the kingdom should be shared — not all reception contexts are appropriate for all sacred content.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The three imperatives — ask, seek, knock — represent an intensifying progression of engagement with God in prayer, reflecting the Jewish conviction that persistent petition honors God. Synagogue prayer practice emphasized repetitive daily prayer (the <em>Amidah</em>, recited three times daily) built on the assumption that regular, persistent address to God was the proper form of covenant relationship. The Talmud preserves traditions about rabbis who prayed persistently until receiving answers (<em>b. Berakhot</em> 32a on Moses\xe2\x80\x99 forty-day intercession as the model).</p>',
    "8": '<p>The promise that "everyone who asks receives" operates on the covenantal assumption that God is reliably faithful to his people\xe2\x80\x99s petitions. The present tense verbs (<em>lambanei, heuriskei, anoigetai</em> = receives, finds, is opened) suggest not a single transaction but an ongoing covenant reality. Jewish prayer theology distinguished between prayers that were answered immediately and those whose answer was delayed but certain; the point is God\xe2\x80\x99s reliability, not automatic immediate fulfillment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The father-son analogies (vv.9-10) draw on Palestinian subsistence economy. Bread (<em>artos</em>) was the staple food; fish (<em>ichthys</em>) from the Sea of Galilee supplemented the diet of Galilean households. A stone (round, flat) superficially resembles a flat loaf of bread; a snake superficially resembles a fish eel. The analogies work because they describe a recognizable deception that any parent would find unthinkable — the cultural horror of a father deceiving his hungry child.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The snake/fish substitution continues the absurdity: eels and other elongated fish were caught in the Sea of Galilee and were a common food source. The analogies assume the audience knows these foods and the visual resemblance that makes the deception scenarios imaginable but morally monstrous.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The <em>a fortiori</em> argument (how much more) — moving from human fatherly goodness to divine fatherly goodness — was a standard Jewish hermeneutical method called <em>qal wahomer</em> (light to heavy). If even flawed human fathers provide good things for their children, how much more will the perfectly good heavenly Father do so? The designation of humans as "evil" (<em>ponēroi</em>) in this context does not mean morally depraved but acknowledges the moral fallibility of human nature in contrast to divine perfection.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The Golden Rule is found in negative form in Hillel\xe2\x80\x99s famous exchange with a prospective proselyte: "What is hateful to you, do not do to your neighbor — that is the whole Torah, all the rest is commentary; go and learn" (<em>b. Shabbat</em> 31a). The same principle appears in Tobit 4:15, Sirach 31:15, and Philo. Jesus gives it a positive formulation and explicitly grounds it in "the Law and the Prophets" — presenting it not as a new rule but as the summary of Israel\xe2\x80\x99s covenant ethics. The positive form requires more active engagement than the negative form\xe2\x80\x99s simple restraint.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The Two Ways tradition — the contrast between the way of life and the way of death — is a foundational structure in Deuteronomic theology (Deut 30:15-20; Jer 21:8), Psalm 1, Wisdom of Ben Sira, the Manual of Discipline from Qumran (1QS 3:13-4:26), and the early Christian <em>Didache</em> (chs. 1-6). Jesus activates this tradition with the gate and road imagery, making entry through the narrow gate and travel on the difficult road the prerequisite for life. The gate (<em>pylē</em>) may evoke the Temple gate where covenant-keeping was required for entry (Ps 118:20).</p>',
    "14": '<p>The spatial metaphors — narrow gate, constricted road — contrast with the wide gate and broad road. In Palestinian topography, main roads between cities were built wide for commerce and military movement; the narrow paths were minor paths between villages or through difficult terrain. The constriction is not arbitrary difficulty but the inherent costliness of covenant faithfulness vs. the ease of accommodation to surrounding culture. The emphasis that "few find it" is realistic about covenant faithfulness across Israel\xe2\x80\x99s history.</p>',
    "15": '<p>False prophets were a recognized social reality in Second Temple Judaism. The <em>Didache</em> (11:7-12) devotes substantial attention to testing prophets. Jewish law provided tests for false prophecy (Deut 18:20-22) and the community at Qumran developed elaborate procedures for evaluating prophetic claims. The "wolves in sheep\xe2\x80\x99s clothing" metaphor draws on shepherd culture: a wolf disguised in a fleece could penetrate the flock and cause mass destruction before being identified. The point is that external religious appearance (<em>en endymasi probatōn</em> = in garments of sheep) can be completely deceptive.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Fruit-testing as a method of evaluating prophetic claims has roots in OT discernment traditions. Jeremiah tested false prophets by their message\xe2\x80\x99s conformity to Torah (Jer 23:9-40); Isaiah tested by the outcome of predictions (Isa 8:20). Jesus shifts the test to the character fruits produced in the prophet and their followers. Palestinian agriculture provided the obvious analogy: grape vines and thorn bushes (<em>akanthōn</em> = thorns) and fig trees and thistles (<em>tribolōn</em>) were familiar flora; the point is that plant-type determines fruit-type invariably.</p>',
    "17": '<p>The principle of good tree/good fruit operates on a horticultural reality well-known to Galilean subsistence farmers who depended on their orchards. A tree\xe2\x80\x99s root health, soil, and variety determined fruit quality; no amount of surface treatment changed the tree\xe2\x80\x99s fundamental productive capacity. The analogy argues for character-rooted holiness: surface religious performance cannot compensate for a rotten inner nature.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The impossibility — a good tree cannot produce bad fruit, a bad tree cannot produce good fruit — employs agricultural determinism as a theological argument. In the ancient world, grafting was practiced but was understood as a radical intervention that changed a branch\xe2\x80\x99s productive nature; Paul uses grafting as an analogy for Gentile inclusion precisely because it is extraordinary (Rom 11:17-24). Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 point is about the <em>natural</em> correspondence between inner character and outward fruit.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The image of cutting down and throwing into fire draws on OT agricultural judgment metaphors (Isa 10:33-34; Dan 4:14) and John the Baptist\xe2\x80\x99s axe-at-the-root warning (3:10). The severity of the image — not pruning but total removal — matches the seriousness of false prophecy as a communal danger. The stakes for the community are high: false prophets mislead the flock toward destruction.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The repetition of the fruit-test summary (echoing v.16) creates a structural envelope around the false prophets section. The inclusio technique (beginning and ending with the same statement) was a recognized literary device in both Jewish and Hellenistic rhetoric to signal the completion of a thematic unit.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The warning that not all who say "Lord, Lord" will enter the kingdom addresses the charismatic prophetic culture of first-century Judaism and early Christianity, where claims of Spirit-driven miracle-working and prophecy were common currency. The Qumran community, various prophetic movements, and early Christian communities all featured individuals who claimed divine authorization. The scenario anticipates judgment-day performance reviews: those who invoked divine authority (<em>tō̄ sō̄ onomati</em> = in your name) but lacked genuine covenant obedience will be excluded.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The threefold appeal — prophecy, exorcism, miracles — in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 name represents the full range of first-century Jewish and early Christian charismatic activity. Exorcism (<em>ekballein daimonia</em>) was practiced by Jewish exorcists and associated with both authoritative figures and itinerant practitioners (cf. Matt 12:27; Acts 19:13-16). Powerful deeds (<em>dynameōn</em>) as divine endorsement was a pervasive assumption; Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching insists that miraculous activity is neither necessary nor sufficient evidence of genuine covenant standing.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The judicial declaration "I never knew you" (<em>oudepote egnōn hymas</em>) employs the Hebrew usage of "know" (<em>yāda</em>) as covenant recognition — to be "known" by God is to be in covenant relationship (Amos 3:2; Hos 13:5; Gen 4:1). The departure command "depart from me, workers of lawlessness" (<em>ergazomenoi tēn anomian</em>) echoes Ps 6:8 LXX, a psalm of the righteous sufferer appealing to God against his enemies. The citation signals that the excluded ones belong with the psalmist\xe2\x80\x99s adversaries, not with the covenant community.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The concluding parable of the two builders employs Palestinian topography: in the dry season, dry wadis (<em>nahal</em>) and their sandy riverbeds appeared to be safe building sites. The rainy season (October-April) brought flash floods that transformed these riverbeds into destructive torrents with little warning. Building on the rock required more effort — clearing debris, cutting into stone for foundations — but survived precisely because it engaged the hard reality. The two builders represent two responses to Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching: hearing and doing vs. hearing and not doing.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The storm elements — rain, rivers flooding, winds (<em>brechē, potamoi, anemoi</em>) — correspond to actual Palestinian weather. The rainy season storms came from the Mediterranean, producing driving rain; the flooding wadis (<em>potamoi</em>) rushed down hillsides toward the valleys; katabatic winds descended from elevated terrain. The house built on rock (<em>petra</em>) — bedrock rather than sandy alluvium — withstood all three forces. The word "fell" (<em>epesen</em>) is conspicuously absent for the rock-built house (v.25 ends without "and it fell"), making the contrast structurally complete at v.27.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The fool who builds on sand represents those who engage with Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching as interesting discourse but make no behavioral commitment. In Jewish Wisdom tradition, the fool (<em>mōros</em>) is not intellectually deficient but is someone who hears wisdom and fails to act on it (Prov 1:7; 9:13-18). The sand (<em>ammos</em>) as a building substrate was visually similar to the rock-and-sandy-soil hillsides of Galilee — the surface appearance was acceptable; the structural failure only became apparent under load.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The destruction of the sand-built house — "and great was its fall" (<em>kai ēn hē ptōsis autēs megalē</em>) — ends the Sermon on the Mount with an eschatological warning of catastrophic collapse for those who hear without doing. The architectural metaphor carries communal weight: a collapsed house was a social and economic catastrophe in the ancient world, not merely an inconvenience. The image foreshadows the temple destruction warning of 24:2 and serves as the Sermon\xe2\x80\x99s final note: covenantal hearing requires covenantal doing.</p>',
    "28": '<p>The crowd\xe2\x80\x99s astonishment (<em>exeplēssonto</em>) at Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 teaching introduces the repeated Matthean contrast between Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 authority (<em>exousia</em>) and the scribes\xe2\x80\x99 method. Scribal teaching operated through chains of citation — "Rabbi X said in the name of Rabbi Y" — tracing opinion back through recognized authorities. The Mishnah\xe2\x80\x99s tractates are structured around attributed sayings that provide authoritative precedents. Jesus taught without citations, speaking from his own authority: "But I say to you" (<em>egō de legō hymin</em>, 5:22 etc.), a formula without parallel in scribal tradition. This was not innovation but claimed unique divine authorization.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The contrast between Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 authority and the scribes was structural, not merely stylistic. The <em>soperim</em> (scribes) were professional experts in the written Torah who also transmitted and developed the oral Torah. Their social role was as legal interpreters who mediated between the written text and community practice. Their authority derived from their place in a chain of tradition extending back to Sinai (Mishnah <em>Avot</em> 1:1). Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 self-authorizing teaching form implied a claim that bypassed this entire tradition-chain, appearing to both audiences and opponents as either profoundly authoritative or dangerously presumptuous.</p>'
  },
  "8": {
    "1": '<p>The transition from the Sermon to the healing narratives (8:1-9:34) follows a deliberate literary pattern: Matthew moves from teaching to demonstration, showing the kingdom in words and then in deeds. The descent from the mountain echoes Moses\xe2\x80\x99 descent from Sinai (Exod 32:1), and the gathering crowd (<em>ochloi polloi</em>) represents the broad population of Galilee who sought both teaching and healing. Matthew groups the ten healing/miracle accounts of chs. 8-9 in a structured arrangement, though the historical occasions were likely scattered across Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Leprosy in the ancient world designated a range of skin diseases beyond modern Hansen\xe2\x80\x99s disease, all subject to Levitical purity regulations (Lev 13-14). The afflicted person was required to live outside the community, wear torn clothes, leave hair disheveled, cover the upper lip, and cry "unclean, unclean" when approached (Lev 13:45-46). This was total social, economic, and religious exclusion — the leper was cut off from family, trade, synagogue, and Temple. His approach to Jesus (violating the isolation protocol) and prostration (<em>prosekynei</em>) before him was a desperate act of hope against established social order.</p>',
    "3": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 physical touch of the leper was itself a violation of purity norms — touching a person with a skin disease created ritual impurity (Lev 5:3). Rather than becoming impure, Jesus demonstrates that his holiness is communicative in the reverse direction: he conveys cleanness rather than receiving uncleanness. The physical contact was a profound act of social restoration even before the cure; the leper had likely not been touched in years. The healing is immediate (<em>eutheōs</em>) and complete (<em>ekatharisthē autou hē lepra</em>).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The command to show the healed man to the priest and offer the required sacrifice (Lev 14:1-32) served two purposes: (1) it respected the Mosaic system by allowing official verification of the cure and legal readmission to community life; (2) it would function as a <em>martyrion</em> (testimony) to the priests — evidence that messianic healing was occurring. The specific offering of Lev 14 included two birds, cedar wood, scarlet yarn, and hyssop, followed by eight days of rites and final animal sacrifices; this was an elaborate, costly procedure that underlined the seriousness of restoration from exclusion.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The Capernaum centurion was likely an officer in Herod Antipas\xe2\x80\x99s service rather than directly in the Roman legions, since Galilee was a client kingdom with its own military force that included non-Jewish officers. Centurions commanded units of approximately 80-100 men; they were career soldiers, the backbone of the Roman and client military structure. Their social position was that of patrons with significant local power and influence — they could build synagogues (Luke 7:5 notes this centurion built the Capernaum synagogue) and maintain networks of clients and dependents. The appeal on behalf of a servant (<em>pais</em>) reflects the patron\xe2\x80\x99s responsibility to care for those in his household network.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 willingness to come to the centurion\xe2\x80\x99s house was socially significant: a Jewish teacher entering the home of a Gentile military officer would incur ritual impurity and risk social censure. The tension in the exchange (whether Jesus is asking a question or making a statement in v.7) reflects the genuine boundary being navigated. The centurion\xe2\x80\x99s response (I am not worthy that you should come under my roof) may reflect awareness of this purity concern.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The centurion\xe2\x80\x99s response — "only speak the word and my servant will be healed" — demonstrates understanding of authority structures from military experience. Roman military chains of command operated through verbal orders with absolute effect down the hierarchy: an officer\xe2\x80\x99s word set events in motion without his physical presence. The centurion perceives Jesus as operating within an analogous structure of divine authority: if imperial commands work at a distance, so do divine ones. This is military epistemology applied to the kingdom of God.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The centurion\xe2\x80\x99s self-description — "I am a man under authority, having soldiers under me" — articulates the Roman military principle of delegated command (<em>imperium</em>). A centurion operated under the authority of tribunes and legates but simultaneously exercised his own authority over subordinates. He recognizes Jesus as operating within a similar hierarchical structure of divine authority, from which healing could be commanded at a distance with the same certainty as a military order.</p>',
    "10": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 astonishment (<em>ethaumasen</em>) at the centurion\xe2\x80\x99s faith is one of only two occasions in the Gospels where Jesus is described as marveling (the other is unbelief in Mark 6:6). The declaration that he had found no such great faith in Israel is a pointed reversal: the insider community has not demonstrated the trust that this Gentile military officer has shown. This anticipates the explicit theme of Gentile inclusion and Jewish rejection that develops through Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s narrative.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The eschatological banquet image — many coming from east and west to recline with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom — draws on the great-feast imagery of Isa 25:6-8 and 49:12, where the nations stream to Zion for the eschatological feast. Reclining (<em>anaklithēsontai</em>) at table with the patriarchs implies full covenant membership at the messianic table. The spatial markers "east and west" signal universal geographic scope; they anticipate the Great Commission\xe2\x80\x99s "all nations" (28:19).</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Sons of the kingdom" (<em>hoi huioi tēs basileias</em>) is a Semitic idiom meaning those who belong to the kingdom by birthright — Israelites who assumed covenant membership as their ethnic inheritance. The warning that they will be cast into outer darkness (<em>to skotos to exōteron</em>) — Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s formula for eschatological judgment — is one of the earliest explicit warnings in Matthew that covenant membership is not guaranteed by ethnic heritage. The prophetic tradition had consistently challenged inherited-security assumptions (Amos 3:2; Jer 7:4-7).</p>',
    "13": '<p>The healing at a distance — "as you have believed, let it be done for you" (<em>hōs episteutsas genēthētō soi</em>) — occurs without Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 physical presence at the location, confirming the centurion\xe2\x80\x99s analysis of authority. The servant was healed "in that hour" (<em>en tē̄ hōra̧ ekeinē̄</em>), connecting the moment of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 word with the moment of the cure even across physical distance.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The healing of Peter\xe2\x80\x99s mother-in-law occurs in Capernaum, identified elsewhere as Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 adopted home base in Galilee (4:13). The house (<em>oikia</em>) of Peter (and Andrew) served as a headquarters for Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 Galilean ministry (Mark 1:29-31 is more detailed). The fever (<em>pyressousa</em>) in the pre-antibiotic Mediterranean world could be life-threatening; its sudden departure upon Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 touch was immediately recognizable as healing rather than natural recovery. Her immediate service (<em>diēkonei</em>) following healing demonstrates the Matthean pattern: healing issues in discipleship-service.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The act of touching her hand (<em>hapsato tēs cheiros autēs</em>) repeated the touch pattern of the leper healing (8:3): physical contact as both healing mechanism and social restoration. Women with fever would be considered ritually impure; Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 touch again communicates purification rather than incurring pollution. Her arising and serving (<em>diēkonei autō̄</em>) is both the practical result of restored health and a brief portrait of restored social function.</p>',
    "16": '<p>The evening healings — after sunset on the Sabbath (<em>opsias de genomenes</em>) — allowed Torah-observant Jews to bring their sick once the Sabbath restrictions ended at nightfall. Sabbath prohibitions on carrying (<em>hotza\'ah</em>) and medical treatment (beyond emergency situations) would have prevented bringing large numbers of sick during the day. The crowd\xe2\x80\x99s gathering at sunset reflects a community that took Sabbath observance seriously while also seeking Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 healing ministry. <em>Daimonizoumenous pollous</em> (many who were possessed by demons) reflects the widespread ancient understanding that illness, mental disturbance, and social disfunction were demonically caused.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Matthew\xe2\x80\x99s fulfillment citation — Isa 53:4 ("he took our weaknesses and bore our diseases") — is applied to healing miracles, not the atonement, which is a significant interpretive decision. The Hebrew of Isa 53:4 (<em>nasa cholayenu, sebal mak\'obenu</em> = carried our sicknesses, bore our pains) is applied by Matthew to Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 physical healings rather than to the cross, suggesting that the Servant\xe2\x80\x99s bearing is already active in Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry, not only at Calvary. The LXX renders it differently (<em>hamartias hēmōn pherei</em> = bears our sins), but Matthew follows the Hebrew sense for this application.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The command to depart to the other side (<em>eis to peran</em>) — the east shore of the Sea of Galilee — initiates a movement away from the Jewish population centers of western Galilee toward the Gentile-influenced Decapolis region. The crowd (<em>ochlon</em>) pressing around Jesus motivates the move; the subsequent scenes will occur in Gentile territory. The Sea of Galilee crossings in Matthew serve as narrative hinges between Jewish and Gentile sectors of Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The scribe\xe2\x80\x99s offer to follow Jesus "wherever you go" represents the voluntary discipleship commitment of an educated Torah-professional to a teacher. Scribal discipleship involved leaving one\xe2\x80\x99s established position to travel with and learn from a rabbi. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 response about foxes and birds having homes — while the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head — is a realistic description of the itinerant teaching life: dependent on hospitality, without a permanent base. This was the actual economic and social situation of traveling teachers in antiquity.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The foxes/birds contrast with the Son of Man\xe2\x80\x99s homelessness draws on the honor vocabulary of the ancient world, where having a home and household (<em>oikos</em>) was the foundation of social identity and stability. A person without a fixed domicile was socially marginal — dependent, mobile, outside the normal patron-client networks that provided economic security. Jesus describes discipleship as entering exactly this socially precarious position, subverting the assumption that following a powerful teacher would bring enhanced social status.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The request to "first bury my father" invoked the highest obligation in Jewish family law. Burial of the dead was a <em>mitzwah</em> (commandment) so significant that it superseded Sabbath observance, Temple service, and the study of Torah (<em>b. Berakoth</em> 3:1; <em>m. Berakhot</em> 3:1). Even a High Priest, normally forbidden to become ritually impure by contact with a corpse, was required to bury a neglected corpse if no one else was present. The disciple\xe2\x80\x99s request was therefore not an excuse but an appeal to the most compelling family obligation in his tradition.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 response — "let the dead bury their own dead" — is among the most radical sayings in the Synoptics, deliberately overriding the Torah\xe2\x80\x99s most pressing family obligation with the kingdom\xe2\x80\x99s claim. The saying employs a paradox: those who are spiritually dead can fulfill the biological obligation; those called to life must follow the life-giver. The shocking reversal of family-duty hierarchy — placing kingdom-following above burial of one\xe2\x80\x99s own parent — signals the absolute priority of the kingdom call over all cultural and religious claims, however legitimate.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The Sea of Galilee sits approximately 210 meters below sea level in a basin surrounded by higher terrain, including the Golan Heights plateau to the east and the hills of Galilee to the west. This topography creates conditions for sudden, violent storms: warm air rising from the lake surface collides with cool air descending from the surrounding highlands, generating katabatic winds (<em>katabatein</em> = descending) that can transform calm conditions into dangerous squalls within minutes. Fishermen on the lake knew this and typically stayed close to shore in questionable conditions; the crossing to the far side was undertaken in the evening at Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 command.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The storm (<em>seismos megas</em> = great shaking, the earthquake word applied to the sea) covered the boat with waves (<em>kalyptesthai hypo tōn kymatōn</em>). Galilean fishing boats of the first century (a well-preserved example from this era was recovered from the lake in 1986) were typically 8-9 meters long, open-decked, and crewed by 4-5 people with room for passengers. They were maneuverable in normal conditions but vulnerable in severe storms. Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 sleeping (<em>ekatheyden</em>) during the storm reflects genuine exhaustion from ministry activity.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 cry "save us, Lord, we are perishing" (<em>sōson, apollym etha</em>) is simultaneously a literal request and a template of distress-petition to God. The OT Psalms of lament (especially Ps 69:1-2; 107:23-30) describe righteous sufferers crying out to God from the chaos of stormy seas. Ps 107:28-29 specifically describes the Lord stilling a storm in response to cry: "He silenced the storm... the waves were hushed." The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 cry is both visceral fear and (unknowing) appropriate covenantal prayer.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The rebuke of the disciples (<em>oligopistoi</em> = little-faith ones) before the stilling of the storm places the address in exactly the right order for teaching: their fear is addressed first, then the natural world is commanded. The rebuke of the wind and sea (<em>epetimēsen tois anemois kai tē̄ thalassē̄</em>) echoes the OT creation vocabulary where God rebukes the primordial waters (Ps 18:15; 104:7; Job 26:11-12). The stilling of the sea was in Jewish thought a divine act; the Psalmist attributes it to YHWH (Ps 65:7; 89:9; 107:29). The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 question "what sort of man is this?" reflects appropriate wonder at an act that was theologically categorized as God\xe2\x80\x99s alone.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The disciples\xe2\x80\x99 amazement and the question "what sort of man is this?" (<em>potapos estin houtos</em>) echoes the crowd\xe2\x80\x99s repeated astonishment at Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 authority throughout chapters 7-8. The question remains unanswered narratively at this point, functioning as a progressive revelation that reaches its climax in Peter\xe2\x80\x99s confession (16:16). The winds and sea obeying is connected to the stilling of the storm in Ps 107:29 where "he stilled the storm to a whisper; the waves of the sea were hushed" — and the response is "they were glad when it grew calm, and he guided them to their desired haven."</p>',
    "28": '<p>The Gadarene territory was part of the Decapolis — a league of ten Hellenistic cities east of the Jordan river with predominantly Gentile populations. Gadara (modern Umm Qays) was a prosperous city with Greek and Roman cultural features; the presence of a large swine herd is consistent with Gentile territory where pig-keeping was economically important. The two demoniacs (<em>demonizomenoi dyo</em> — Matthew, characteristically, doubles the Mark/Luke single figure) came from the tombs, a place of corpse-impurity for Jews, underlining the extreme degree of their exclusion from human community.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The demons\xe2\x80\x99 cry "what have we to do with you, Son of God? Have you come here to torment us before the time?" (<em>pro kairou</em> = before the appointed time) reflects an understanding of cosmological eschatology: the final judgment and confinement of evil spirits was expected at the end of the age. The demons recognize Jesus and understand his authority to command them; their concern is that the appointed time of their imprisonment has not yet arrived. This eschatological awareness on the part of demonic forces is consistent with Second Temple Jewish angelology and demonology (1 Enoch 10:4-6; Jubilees 10:7-9).</p>',
    "30": '<p>The large herd of pigs (<em>agelē choirōn pollōn</em>) grazing nearby confirms the Gentile character of the territory. For a Jewish audience, the detail is loaded with cultural associations: swine were the paradigmatic unclean animal, their presence signaling the complete ritual otherness of the region. For the demonized men, the swine offer the demons an alternative habitation in exchange for releasing their human hosts — a form of negotiated exorcism that Jesus grants.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The demons\xe2\x80\x99 request to enter the swine rather than be sent away (<em>apo tēs chōras</em> = out of the region) reflects ancient beliefs about demonic territorial attachment. Demons were often understood as bound to particular geographic areas or requiring embodied habitation. The permission Jesus grants is ironic: the unclean spirits enter the unclean animals and immediately drive them to destruction, suggesting that demonic habitation is inherently destructive.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The rush of the pigs into the sea (<em>hormēsen pasa hē agelē kata tou krēmnou eis tēn thalassan</em>) is a scene with multiple layers: the economic loss of a large herd was significant (two thousand swine in Mark\xe2\x80\x99s version), representing a substantial financial catastrophe for the herders and owners. The sea, associated in Jewish cosmology with chaos and demonic forces (cf. Rev 13:1; 21:1 "the sea was no more"), becomes the appropriate receptacle for these spirits. The destruction is total and immediate.</p>',
    "33": '<p>The herders fled and reported to the city — the economic impact of losing the herd would have been the primary concern of the owners. The report spreads to "the city and the country" (<em>tēn polin kai tous agrous</em>), indicating a significant settlement nearby. The public response (v.34) — the whole city coming out to meet Jesus — frames the Gentile community\xe2\x80\x99s reaction to the event.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The townspeople\xe2\x80\x99s request that Jesus depart from their region (<em>hopōs metabē apo tōn horiōn autōn</em>) prioritizes the economic stability of the region over the liberation of the two demoniacs. The economic cost of the pig herd outweighed, in their calculus, the social benefit of the men\xe2\x80\x99s restoration. The rejection of Jesus in Gentile territory anticipates the pattern that will recur: Jesus\xe2\x80\x99 ministry generates both liberation and disruption, and some communities prefer the familiar disruption of the status quo to the costly freedom Jesus offers. Jesus complies and departs.</p>'
  }
}

